content.description: The Castle is a spire North of the Dikes climbing area. There are two bolted climbs to the top of the spire. The rock is not great and the approach is terrible, but the exposure and view are awesome.
content.location: Park on the side of the road and bushwhack/scramble your way up the hillside to the base of the spire.

content.description: Vertical start leads to a comfortable clip, pull the overhanging crux and rest.
content.protection: 4 bolts to shuts. Bolts are difficult to find initially and I would suggest a stick clip start. Shuts are on the North facing wall. I pulled off a ton of moss so they are exposed, for now.
content.location: Second route from the North on the West side Megadike North.

content.description: Start in a cave with a large and small pocket. Move through the overhang with pretty great moves, knee bar is suggested, and move through the vertical (5.7ish) finish before you pump out. Rock is surprisingly solid.
content.protection: Bolts are difficult to see. Chain anchors not visible from the ground, don't confuse with the shiny chains to the right.
content.location: 25" uphill from Incoming. Look for large pockets in the rock where a small cave exists.

content.description: Start on the vertical section and move through less and less difficult terrain to the first anchors, or second depending on the path you chose. Second pitch goes to the right and up a headwall (don't worry its 8 feet high) and then past the three bolt anchor of Incoming and to the pinnacle of the formation.
content.location: Left of Lady Slipper, the second vertical starting route on the face.

content.description: Slightly wandering route. Belay from sharp talus.
content.location: Second route from the North on Megadike South.

content.description: Long moderate slabby arete on the south edge of a pinnacle known as black tooth.
content.location: Megadike South

content.description: Lead to and around the arete.
Smooth, mossy start leads to a nice vertical middle section and mild finish.
content.protection: Unk number of bolts to chains.
content.location: To the right of Just Enough

content.description: Overhanging start leads to ledge. Pine needles and moss will frustrate.
content.location: To the left of Red Zinger, see map for details.

content.description: Start from right (East) side of the dike and follow the bolts through loose blocks to anchor. Seems to be two routes with one start. The left side is loose blocks and minimal 5th class. The right is more vertical and goes at 5.5.
content.protection: UNK bolts 6-7 possibly, anchor on left variation is Quicklinks on hangers and shuts on the right variation.
content.location: North of the Megadike North area. No obvious trail, but coming from the East is preferred.

content.description: Great holds all the way. Can be dirty, be prepared to clean holds.
content.location: Megadike South (See Megadike South Map)

content.description:
Great holds and easy clipping. Follow the line without moss. The second pitch is the same grade if you follow the correct route.

*Pitches can be linked with a 70m rope, but barely so tie your cat knot.*
content.location: Final route before you go around the dike's north face.

content.description: Start from small holds and move through a little bulge to 5.2 and the chains.
content.location: Off the trail past the break in the Minidike.

content.description: Short route with second "pitch" that goes linked with a 70m and possibly a 60m. The crux has two parallel bolts so you can go right or left at the mini-roofs (go left). Much of the route is low 5.1 with maybe 20' of technical climbing. Be prepared to use alpine draws and back clean to keep rope drag manageable.
content.protection: 3 bolts to wide hangers, then plenty of bolts to chain anchor on a huge ledge.
content.location: First route off the trail to Megadike North. It goes to the top of a 20' pillar and through the Northeast arette.

content.description: Real short route, great for teaching new climbers. A little difficult to get to.
content.location: Minidike (See Minidike map)

content.description:
Start from jugs and move through progressively more difficult holds and moves until you reach the last bolt and wonder where to go.. The crux is before the last bolt, if you got stuck on smooth rock and moss traverse right.

The chains are back and to the left of the last bolt, semi hidden by small trees..
content.protection: 8 Bolts to Chains. The chains are back and to the left of the last bolt, semi hidden by small trees..
content.location: Last route on the face, a little up the talus.

content.description:
The name is self explanatory from the fourth bolt on. Start on the face and move though a constriction (crux) and small roof with great holds. If you chicken out, every tough move can be avoided. Sits in the shade all day, and the view is great from the chains.

Climbing Lady slipper to the summit of the dike will take you to Incoming's chains to set up a TR.
content.protection: 14 bolts to 3 bolt anchor with chains.
content.location: First route on the west side. To the left of the large overhanging area.

content.description: Simple, blocky line.
content.location: West side of the Minidike

content.description:
The crux is the lower portion, holds

should

hold.
content.location: South of Way Up

content.description: Start in the crux and move through the overhanging portion. Eases up and has a great resting point before the chains.
content.protection: 7 bolts to chain anchors Shares anchor with Cheap Beer.
content.location: First route you see from the trail.

content.description: A few jugs and a fist jam get you to, and through the crux.
content.location: Starts just uphill of Bachelor Party, and shares the same anchor point.

content.description: Crimpy/slightly overhanging start leads to great holds and view.
content.location: Last route on North East side of Megadike South.

content.description:
The route moves through a neat set of rock features that resembles stacked wood.

Currently has severe rock fall potential, as the right side has a large amount of stacked blocks that are separated from the main wall by at least an inch and have the potential to be lethal.

*I am posting this route on here so people are made aware of the hazard*
content.location: The route is 30' left (west) of Monkey on separate feature.

content.description: Vertical (crux) start with great bolt placement leads to slabby finish.
content.location: Just South of Red Zinger.

content.description: This is a short two pitch that you can actually top rope with a 60m rope. but, it makes you feel cool if you've never done multi pitch before.
content.location: Minidike

content.description: Short but sweet.
